this ip 172.16.1.0/24 , 172.16.2.0/24 , 172.16.3.0/24 etc. Now i will create internet gateway to access vpc, Now if any user want to access any application running in vpc this person has to come into vpc through this gateway. Now in this vpc there may some subnets which do not have access to internet also know as private subnets but with that there is also free space which is know as public subnets. When users enter in vpc they first land on public subnet and public subnet connect to user or internet through internet gateway. Now after public subnet user goes to load balancer and than through this LB user to application. Load balancer is assigned with public subnet and for the LB we will make a target group of particular application. Now   through LB if request wants to go to any subnet than LB dont know this path so will create route to this subnet which is route table. Now after entering subnet there is also one more guard for ec2 instance which is security groups which will ask from where you are coming and on which ip and port are you going and then finally you will reach application. There is also one more concept which is NACL (network access control list) using this we can aassign same security group to multiple ec2 instances instead of creating individual security groups for instances. There is one more concept of NAT    gateway , now if any application in ec2 which is in private subnet want to access internet for any purpose so this request will go through this NAT, which mask that private ip.

Step-by-step VPC Understanding (Clean Version)

1. Create VPC (your IP pool)
You start by creating a VPC in Amazon Web Services.
Example:
172.16.0.0/16
✔ What this means:
Total IPs = 65,536 (not 255×255 exactly)
Range: 172.16.0.0 → 172.16.255.255
👉 Think of this as your entire private network for the project

2. Create Subnets (divide your network)
You split VPC into smaller chunks:
172.16.1.0/24
172.16.2.0/24
172.16.3.0/24
✔ Each /24 subnet:
256 IPs (251 usable in AWS)
👉 Think:
Each subnet = a smaller network inside VPC
Usually mapped to Availability Zones (AZs)

3. Public vs Private Subnets
Now comes an important concept 👇
🔓 Public Subnet
Has route to Internet Gateway (IGW)
Resources can be accessed from internet (if allowed)
🔒 Private Subnet
NO direct internet access
Used for:
databases
backend services
👉 Important correction:
❌ “Free space is public subnet” → not true
✔ Public/private depends on routing, not free space

4. Internet Gateway (IGW)
You attach an Internet Gateway to your VPC.
👉 Role:
Allows traffic between internet ↔ VPC
But just attaching IGW is NOT enough ❗
You must also configure:
Route Table (for public subnet)
0.0.0.0/0 → IGW
👉 This makes subnet public

5. Entry Point: User Request Flow
Now let’s follow a real request 👇
🌍 Step 1: User sends request
User opens:
https://your-app.com

6. Load Balancer (Entry inside VPC)
You create a Load Balancer using
AWS Elastic Load Balancing
✔ Important:
LB is placed in public subnets
It has:
public IP / DNS
connected to IGW
👉 Correction:
❌ User does NOT “enter public subnet first manually”
✔ User hits Load Balancer, which is inside public subnet

7. Target Group
Load Balancer forwards request to:
👉 Target Group
Contains EC2 instances / services
Defines:
port (e.g., 80, 443)
protocol (HTTP/HTTPS)

8. Routing (Important Correction)
❌ You said:
LB creates route to subnet via route table
✔ Correct:
Route Tables are for network routing (subnet level)
Load Balancer does NOT use route tables to find instances
👉 Instead:
LB uses Target Group
AWS handles internal routing automatically

9. Application Layer (EC2 in Private Subnet)
Your app usually runs on
Amazon EC2 instances
✔ Best practice:
Place EC2 in private subnet
No direct internet exposure
Flow:
User → LB → Target Group → EC2

10. Security Layer (VERY IMPORTANT)
🔐 Security Groups (Instance Level)
Acts like firewall:
Allow:
Source IP
Port
Protocol
Example:
Allow traffic from Load Balancer SG on port 80
🧱 Network ACL (Subnet Level)
Optional extra layer:
Works at subnet level
Stateless

🔁 Final Flow (Clean Diagram in Words)
User (Internet)
     ↓
Internet Gateway (IGW)
     ↓
Public Subnet
     ↓
Load Balancer (public)
     ↓
Target Group
     ↓
Private Subnet
     ↓
EC2 Instance (your app)
     ↓
Security Group check
     ↓
Application responds
